      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing, let's compare the two:\n\nMitosis results in two identical daughter cells, each with the same number of chromosomes as the parent cell. It's like cloning – you get an exact copy. Mitosis is used for growth, repair, and asexual reproduction.\n\nMeiosis, on the other hand, results in four genetically unique daughter cells, each with half the number of chromosomes as the parent cell. It's like a mix-and-match process, creating genetic diversity. Meiosis is used for sexual reproduction, producing gametes (sperm and eggs).\n\nSo, the main difference is that mitosis creates identical cells for growth and repair, while meiosis creates diverse cells for sexual reproduction.",
