      "content": "Absolutely, let's dive into the details of anaphase:\n\nDuring anaphase, the sister chromatids are pulled apart by the spindle fibers. These fibers are attached to the centromeres of each chromosome, which are the regions where the chromatids are joined together.\n\nThe spindle fibers are made of microtubules, which are like tiny, flexible rods. They extend from the two poles of the cell, where the spindle apparatus is anchored. The microtubules have motor proteins called dyneins and kinesins that move along them, pulling the chromatids toward the opposite poles.\n\nThink of the spindle fibers as the strings that hold the chromatids together. During anaphase, the motor proteins start to pull on these strings, causing the chromatids to separate and move toward opposite ends of the cell. It's like a tug-of-war, where the motor proteins are the players pulling on the strings.\n\nOnce the chromatids reach the poles, they are considered individual chromosomes. This separation ensures that each daughter cell will receive an equal number of chromosomes, maintaining the genetic consistency of the organism.\n\nI hope that helps you visualize the process better!",
